Exploring data

To get an overview of the data set, I use the dim() and summary() function to explore the data.

dim(laptop)
## [1] 896  23

We can see that the laptop data set has 23 columns and 896 rows.

There are 896 observations or rows in this data set, and each of them is a kind of laptop that is on the market.

Missing data

Next, we are looking at the missing data.

There are only 3 variables that contains missing data which are model (10.6%), processor generation (26.67%), and display size (37.05%). Overall, 3.2% of data is missing and the rest 96.8% is present.

Question 1

  • How does different gigabytes of RAM affect laptop prices?

To answer this question, I used box plot to see the distribution of price throughout different amount of gigabyte.

Answer: We can see that the median price for 4 GB RAM is just over 5000 dollar, and gradually increase - 8 GB is around 1000, 16 GB is above 15000, and drastically increase at 32 GB at the price of 25,000. In conclusion, we can say that the more gigabyte RAM has, the more expensive laptop will be

ggplot(laptop, aes(x=ram_gb, y=old_price)) + geom_boxplot() + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(vjust = 0.5, hjust=1))+
  scale_x_discrete("ram_gb", limits = c("4 GB GB","8 GB GB","16 GB GB","32 GB GB"), 
                   labels = c("4 GB GB" = "4 GB",
                              "8 GB GB" = "8 GB",
                              "16 GB GB"= "16 GB",
                              "32 GB GB"= "32 GB"))

Question 2

  • Which brand has the highest diminishing value in their laptop over time?

In the data set, we have 2 variable regarding prices which are original prices and latest price. Over the year, prices of laptop will have a discount because of the evolving technology and innovation. The answer to this question will help us to understand which brand has the lower value of laptops. We are using a bar plot to answer this question.

Answer: We can see that Lenovo and Vaio whose discount rate are just under 50% have the highest diminishing value in their laptop over time. Brands with low discount rate are Smartron, Apple, and Microsoft.

ggplot(data=laptop) +
  geom_bar(aes(x=brand, y = discount),
           stat = "summary",
           fun = "mean", width=0.75) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, vjust = 0.5))
